story:
The covid 19 restrictions effect almost everything we do and planning a funeral is no different. Being restricted to 20 people is very tough and it’s very hard knowing there are friends and family that cannot pay their respects in the “normal” way. The restrictions also mean that charities do not receive the amount of money in donations that they usually would. Charities rely on donations to do the work they do and it’s troubling to think of how this has been effected during the pandemic. 

I want to give back to Macmillan cancer support in honour of my dads memory. The local Macmillan department provided an excellent service of care during his short illness, going above and beyond to ensure he was well cared for. 

I’m sharing this page to allow others to donate if they wish to do so. 

In memory of a fantastic Dad, grandad, brother, friend and boss. A true legend who will be missed by all that knew him.
title: In memory of Stevie Paterson

story:
This year has been an awful nightmare for everyone. Thinking of my own childhood compared to how every child has suffered this year made me want to do something special  So i thought of what my Late Father would of done. We decided to have a goal to make every child smile that passes our home, and in the process raise money for a very special cause that related to us. Our aim was to Gift A Smile For Christmas. We have spent alot of time decorating our house with variety of Christmas lights and we have made a walkthrough garden where everyone can come and see.

If we can gift a smile at christmas and raise money for This cause then that would make us hit our goal

story: Hi everyone!! EGGsausted many many many puns thinking of what to call this page ! More so very welcomed So basically I am shaving my hair off in the hope that you lovely lot will help me raise some propper good mega dosh for three amazing charities Yes three, I couldn't settle on one and had to narrow it down because they' re all so wonderful ! I narrowed it down finally MIND - 1in4 of us experiance mental health issues every year and with the impact of 2020 mental health support is crucial, MIND offers the support and information. and undoubtedly saves lives MACMILLIAN - Amazing charity offering support to those suffering with cancer and LOROS which is an incredable Leicester based hospice that runs entirely from donations Well, four charities if you include my hair donation to The Little Princess Trust which is absolutly amazing and makes wigs for little ones who need them. I'd absolutly love to hit 3k as then thats a lovely 1k to each charity but I'd also like to absolutly smash that figure out of the park too , I know its has been a terrible year for all of us in our little lifeboats bobing along tring cloing on with white knuckles and ride the psunami of the rona and 2020 goings on so please give what you can because what these services consistantly provide is absolutly paramont. Please have a dig in your pockets and donate what you can ,I dont want to be baldilocks and the three hairs for a tenner you know!

eventName: In memory of Hari Singh Ubhi
story:
Hari Singh Ubhi was a beloved father, grandfather and great-grandfather, who we all loved with all our hearts. He was a survivor of prostate cancer and donated regularly to Macmillan as he always believed in helping others. 

He recently passed away unexpectedly from non-cancer or covid related health complications leaving a massive hole in our lives. We wanted to set up this page in his memory, in the hope that we can inspire people to give back to cancer support services as he did. 

Please donate whatever you can, we all really appreciate it X

story: This time last year I received the devastating news that I had breast cancer. Thankfully I had a FANTASTIC team who have now made me a CANCER SURVIVOR!! Part of that team was the most amazing MacMillan nurse – Jane. Jane was always at the end of the phone or an email to answer all of my questions and to check in on me. When you get diagnosed with cancer, you are assigned a MacMillan nurse and they are the greatest resource ever! So many people have been impacted by this horrible disease and supported by MacMillan Cancer Support. We are raising as much money as we can to ensure others will have the same support that I had. I am no cyclist, I am about to cycle 178 miles/286 KMs over 3 days! London - Bruges, over BIG hills, along windy coastal roads and navigating the traffic out of London. This is a major challenge for me. It is also a real privilege to do this with family and friends. We are 21 in total - this is a mixed ability group and for most of us this will be our 1st cycling road challenge and is a HUGE challenge :-) So please dig deep and give as much as you can for this worthy cause. We will do you proud and suffer the saddle sores!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting our page. 

This half term, we have been learning about the heart, our circulatory system and how we can keep our bodies fit and healthy. On Thursday 10th December, we have planned a fundraising event to help raise money for the British Heart Foundation and would be very grateful for your support. From 9:00-3:00, we will be skipping continuously in the playground on a rotation. Everyone of us will skip for 4 minutes each, meaning that in total, we will skip for 6 hours straight!

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target.

Thanks!

For those of you unaware I am a diabetic and struggle with this fact on a daily basis. I also struggle mentally with diabetes and challenges like this keep me focused as well as helping out worthwhile charities. I'd be so grateful for your support and I know the charity will be too. This is why I am doing the winter walk marathon. 26.2 gruelling miles!! 

For those of you who don't know, these sort of challenges come at a cost. I can pay a high, middle or low fee and am expected to raise a certain amount according to the fee. Any shortfall I will have to make up personally. I am offering a prize to one lucky person who has donated in what I've saved in entrance fee in the attempt to smash the target raised. 

For every £10 donated you can have a guess at my time to completed this task. It's all above board, in black n white. Leave within Facebook comments or donation comments. The winner will be the one who is closest to my finish time. You will win a £50 Amazon voucher. So if you donate £10 one guess, £20 two guesses and so on. Good luck.

story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

charity.description: We fundraise to enhance Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people. Donations help to fund advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, pioneering research and rebuilding and refurbishment.
charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
eventName: The Castle School to Great Ormond Street Hospital
story:
Students and teachers in Caernarvon House at The Castle School will be raising money for Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Students within Caernarvon House have chosen GOSH as their charity for the House Enterprise project due to the incredible research, treatment and support they provide to seriously ill babies, children and young adults. Alongside other challenges and fundraising ideas students and staff will be walking and cycling the 150 mile distance from The Castle School to Great Ormond Street Hospital. 

Great Ormond Street has had a significant impact on Mr Jones (Head of Sport and Nutrition) here is his experience of the amazing work they do.

I am doing this bike Ride for Teddy Tweed, my soon to be Godson.

This is Teddys story.
Teddy got his first bout of meningitis at 5 weeks old and his second at 13 weeks. Although there is a vaccine for a few specific strains of meningitis he did not catch these types of meningitis. There are many different strains of meningitis something I was totally unaware
of before Teddy got poorly. The symptoms in neonatal babies is massively under publicised which is why I was so shocked when I was told he was being treated for meningitis before we had a diagnosis. To obtain a specific diagnosis it takes 3 days to grow the bacteria. 

Although he has physically recovered well, He is still working on his communications skills and struggles with trusting people. Teddy is doing so well though and we are all so proud of him. He has just turned 3 years old and Great Ormond Street have literally this week discharged him from immunology which is brilliant news. I am so thankful to all the Staff at GOSH for all their hard work, they are doing a great job. 

Please help donate so we can help even more children in their time of need. Your support will definitely motivate me to do this ride.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit this JustGiving page in Memory of my Dad - Peter Geoffrey Bennett.

Born 10 March 1948. He grew up in Kingston Upon Thames, Surrey, enjoying many sports. He married Jane in 1969 and moved to Cirencester in 1974 where they raised 2 daughters. He was instrumental in designing the Nationwide Flex Account still used today. They moved to Quenington in 1980 along with the old MG SA car which he continued to restore. He was an active church member at Fairford United Church and Cirencester Ashcroft Church, and was a Methodist Lay Preacher for 25 years. He was always interested in the railways and enjoyed many hours volunteering on the local GWSR. He lived life to the full, participating in many events and organisations including Cirencester Swimming Club.  He also enjoyed some very special holidays with the whole family.

He was diagnosed with prostate cancer in August 2020 and though treatment had been going well, complications were too much to fight and he passed peacefully  22 Nov 2020.

He will be much missed.
title: In memory of Peter Geoffrey Bennett

story:
Hello

Last Year before Covid 19  Cambridge Chartered Insurance Institute (CII)  had our big charity fundraiser of the year in December. This year was due to be extra special as it is the 100th anniversary of our institute being established.


Due to obvious reasons, we can't hold the get together this year. With this in mind, I wanted to recognise the centenary by raising funds for charity at the same time... and riding off some of the Turkey dinner before Christmas Day 

During the month of December, I'll be Riding my Gym bike 100 KM  for 100 years of Cambridge CII. The President of Cambridge Nick Casson being more adventurous will be running 100KM


We are raising money for Cancer Research UK. Over recent years, I have had several family members and clients who  have battled cancer and so this is a cause very close to my heart.

story: In September 2020 I lost my Mum to Cancer , the biggest surprise was that 5 weeks prior to losing she was in perfect health . Scary as this is the same happened to Matthew our Transport Manager who lost his dad in a 5 weeks time frame. It was a wake up call for me that Cancer can take people so quickly , some thing that I had no previous comprehension of . Part of CV19 lock down encouraged all of the team at Rexel Leeds to get fit a challenge that they succeeded in losing a combined 10 Stone in 13 weeks. Because the team are still in there top physical peak ...........well kind of!!! I have challenged my work colleagues to travel the distance from Rexel Leeds to Mums old house in Altea Spain starting 1st of December through to the 18th of December . Some good people having a laugh working together and ending up in Spain ..... No better way of remembering my mum

eventName: NQ Health & Social Care - Christmas Appeal
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Marie Curie Christmas appeal – help us raise awareness of the Marie Curie charity and raise funds at the same time! Marie Curie needs your help!

Covid-19 has put a hold on everything from weddings and holidays to restaurants and parties, we wish we could put a hold on terminal illnesses but unfortunately we can’t.

We want to raise awareness of the Marie Curie Charity as we feel there is not enough publicity for the amazing work that they do. Marie Curie urgently need your help to be able to continue their work.

The pandemic has made it extremely difficult for Marie Curie to raise money, fundraisers have been cancelled and charity shops have closed. Without your donations and support, care and support for individuals and their families living with terminal illnesses would not be possible.

 Who is Marie Curie?

  • Marie Curie was born in Warsaw Poland.
  • She is the first woman to win a Nobel prize and to this date, the only person to win a Nobel prize in two different science fields.
  • Marie Curie was a WW1 hero, she developed mobile radiography units by outfitting cars with x-ray equipment and generators to help wounded soldiers.  

 What does the Marie Curie Charity do?

  • They provide support for families of those with terminal illnesses.
  • Provide around the clock care for people living with terminal illnesses
  • Their Hospices provide specialist care
  • They support everyone in the UK through all aspects of dying, death and bereavement.
  • They fight for society, where everyone can lead the best life they can until the end.

 Facts about Marie Curie Charity

  • Only 1 third of Marie Curie’s funding is provided by the NHS, the remaining 2 thirds are funded by supporters, companies and trusts. 
  • Without supporters and donations Marie Curie would not be able to provide vital support and care for people who need them.
  • The yellow daffodil symbolises new beginnings and  rebirth.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Marie Curie are a charity very close to my heart. I was first made aware of this wonderful charity in 2012, when my mum received a terminal cancer diagnosis. They set up a plan for end of live palliative care for her, which I have the firm belief prolonged her life and the time we could spend with her. Not only that, they gave me counselling to help me get through the pain of losing her, especially as I was so young at the time. I've wanted to give something back to the charity for a long time, but unfortunately never had the chance to do so. 

The charity's fundraising efforts have been slowed down due to the Coronavirus pandemic, so I want to help support them, as a thank you for everything they did for me and my family. 


All donations are not essential, but greatly appreciated. 100% of your donation goes direct to the charity themselves, and any donations direct to my channel will also be sent direct to the charity. 

Thank you

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Our nurses, doctors, therapists and social workers provide expert care and support both to the people staying with us at the hospice, and in the local community. 

Each day at the hospice is special. By getting to know people as individuals, we help them do what is important to them  whether thats getting out into the hospice garden to enjoy the views across the sea, having a beloved pet visit come to visit or sharing precious moments with their loved ones.

We need to raise £8,311 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Cardiff and the Vale get the care and support they need.

And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
2020 has been a challenging year, but it has also sparked a renewed appreciation of nature and a reminder of the importance of our homes. Around the world precious habitats are being destroyed at an alarming rate, and every day there are fewer places left that wildlife can call home.

We are taking a stand for nature and walking to raise money for WWF, a charity devoted to working to improve earth. 

WWF ambassador David Attenborough has reiterated time and time again that we are nearing the time of irreparable change and while more of us are demanding national and international change to ensure Earth's longevity and protect endangered species, more needs to be done. 

I urge you to head over to WWF to see what they have already contributed to the growing argument of global warming and their success stories that have already ensured the survival of once where endangered species. . 

They say Christmas is a time of giving... Please give today and contribute to protecting our wildlife and saving so many more species across the world.
title: The WWF Big Winter Wander
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
pageSummary: Me and my partner are walking for wildlife. because no animals should lose the land they call home
pageSummaryWhat: Me and my partner are walking for wildlife.
pageSummaryWhy: no animals should lose the land they call home

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. 

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, me and my friends and family can experience Scotland's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. 

The funds I raise will help WWF campaign, lobby & protect our wildlife, and wildlife around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

Anyone who knows Will knows how much he loves our world and animals. He recently wrote a letter to Boris about 'the bad things in our world' including endangered animals, poaching,  plastic in the ocean and global warming.  He wants to do something to protect our world and this is his perfect opportunity. 

Thank you in advance for your kind donations for this worthy cause 😊

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
We all have fond memories of being fascinated by squirrels scurrying around woodlands and parks, and I know we'd love for our children to experience those precious moments too, but it's becoming less and less likely.
2020 has been a year to forget, apart from the things we took solace in like nature and wildlife. Our amazing creatures and open spaces are in trouble and have been for a while, it's no new news, but every penny that every fundraising campaign gets enables vital conservation work to take place.
I know money is really tight right now, believe me, I've just lost my job, but we'll be losing something far more important to us all. Once it's gone it's gone and we'll be left with only photos of animals that once existed to show our children.
Rio loves long walks and absolutely adores trees and animals and he, along with the support of Mummy and Daddy, will be helping to raise £100 for the WWF. We'd be so very, very grateful for any donations to help such a vital cause. Together we can make a world of difference and save our world for generations to come.
💚 Thank you 💚
 🐿🦔🌳🌻

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
This year the students at Ricards have voted to support UNICEF as their Christmas fundraising charity. 

This year UNICEF has issued its largest ever emergency funding appeal to reach more than 190 million children impacted by humanitarian crisis and the Coronavirus pandemic. Funds will support essential programs for children and their families across 149 countries and territories throughout 21. 

As a school we hope to raise funds to purchase some inspired gifts that will save lives  - just £31 provides protection for a health worker, £16 buys 100 bars of soap and £43 provides a family with an emergency water kit.
title: Ricards Lodge 2020 Christmas Charity Appeal - UNICEF
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February myself and Cam Graetz have set ourselves a challenge to run 300km each throughout the month (averaging 10km a day) in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!

story:
Dear colleagues, now friends.

I would love to receive any kind of amazing gadget for myself, my passion for music, or my insane attraction for good wine. But after thinking a lot,  I decided that this is not the time for ourselves only,. So it would be great if you can help with a fundraising for this organisation, which I am already supporting since 3 years now with monthly donations.

MSF supports the relief of people struggling with diseases in places where there are no hospitals or services to help them, and they are helping people crossing the mediterranean who risking their life to find a better condition.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Not only is Just Water the ultimate detox after an over-indulgent Christmas, but by fundraising for WaterAid you'll be helping to change lives with the gift of clean water. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across the world. 

If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
